{
  "answer": "**No passage in *Ślokāntara* describes the tongue's misuse as the worst of sins (or uses those terms).**\n\nThe text—a commentary on Sanskrit verses (*śloka*) about *dharma* (righteousness), sins (*pātaka*, *mahāpātaka*, etc.), virtues, castes, kingship, women, and cosmology—emphasizes truth (*satya*) as the highest *dharma* and untruth (*anṛta*) as the greatest sin: \"There is no *dharma* greater than truth. There is no sin greater than untruth.\"[^1] It permits five exceptions where falsehood (*anṛta*) incurs no sin: jest (*narma*), protecting life (*prāṇadravyarakṣaṇe*), protecting property, protecting family (*strīṣu*), and sexual union (*vivāhakāle*); all other lies are sinful.[^2]\n\nHarsh or deceitful speech appears indirectly (e.g., hypocrites with \"sweet words\" but scissor-like hearts,[^3] or slanderers among heinous crimes[^4]), but nothing frames tongue misuse as uniquely worst. Sins escalate: *pātaka* (e.g., killing embryos), *upapātaka*, *mahāpātaka* (e.g., killing Brahmins), *atipātaka* (incest, destroying liṅgas). Speech is secondary to violence/theft.\n\nIf the query recalls a different phrasing or work (none match corpus-wide searches for \"tongue\"/\"misuse\"/\"worst sin\"), the Falsafa corpus (37 works) lacks it.\n\n[^1]: *Ślokāntara*, Chapter 1, [paragraph p-bad244](/works/unknown-slokantara-d7a628/01/translation/#p-bad244) (Ślo_07s); [paragraph p-11d11c](/works/unknown-slokantara-d7a628/01/translation/#p-11d11c) (Ślo_07j).\n\n[^2]: *Ślokāntara*, Chapter 1, [paragraph p-77e620](/works/unknown-slokantara-d7a628/01/translation/#p-77e620) (Ślo_22j).\n\n[^3]: *Ślokāntara*, Chapter 1, [paragraph p-8fbb6c](/works/unknown-slokantara-d7a628/01/translation/#p-8fbb6c) (Ślo_34j).\n\n[^4]: *Ślokāntara*, Chapter 1, [paragraph p-200f22](/works/unknown-slokantara-d7a628/01/translation/#p-200f22) (Ślo_32j).",
